se of what the religion could offer. Reintroducing the term “syncretism” for the inevitable and continuous process by which a religion is acculturated, the book addresses the various formations of Egyptian Christianity that developed in the domestic sphere, the worlds of holy men and saints’ shrines, the work of craftsmen and artisans, the culture of monastic scribes, and the reimagination of the landscape itself, through processions, architecture, and the potent remains of the past.Drawing on sermons and magical texts, saints’ lives and figurines, letters and amulets, and comparisons with Christianization elsewhere in the Roman empire and beyond, Christianizing Egypt reconceives religious change—from the “conversion” of hearts and minds to the selective incorporation and application of strategies for protection, authority, and efficacy, and for imagining the environment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aChristianity and other religionsxEgyptian. 0aSyncretism (Religion)zEgypt. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / History.2bisacsh  aAcolyte.  aAmulet.  aAncient Egypt.  aAncient Egyptian deities.  aApocalypse of Elijah.  aApotropaic magic.  aArchaeology.  aBasilica.  aBurial.  aCaesarius of Arles.  aCemetery.  aCeremony.  aChristian art.  aChristian demonology.  aChristian media.  aChristian monasticism.  aChristian theology.  aChristian tradition.  aChristianity.  aChristianization.  aClergy.  aDeity.  aDemonization.  aDemonology.  aDivination.  aEpigraphy.  aExorcism.  aFigurine.  aGod.  aHagiography.  aHarpocrates.  aHeathenry (new religious movement).  aHomily.  aHousehold.  aIconography.  aIdeology.  aImage of God.  aIncense.  aJews.  aJohn Chrysostom.  aLaity.  aLate Antiquity.  aLiterature.  aLiturgy.  aLord's Prayer.  aMagical